title: For Sale:  Buyer BEWARE of crooks in ARMSLIST
postcontent:
Beat up Glocks for $400-$600  !!!??? you nuts?
Used Sig Sauer pistols for the price of a BNIB !!??  you insane?

You got ripped off at Cabella's (or other retailers) overpaying for your gun and now you are trying to get your $ back selling here??  you a moron?

Buyer beware bunch of scammers in here. Crooks buy these items from police returns for $250 or even less and then turn around to ARMSLIST to sell them for more, a lot more. I am not against making a buck, I am against unscrupulous people endangering others: These guns are dangerous nearing their end of service life and in need of full rebuild. They won't tell you that.

Buyer do yourself a favor, check other sites for the real prices. Slickguns, Grab-a-Gun and others post the best values (not inflated) for new weapons and also all those used police returns and cheap imports (like the Sig 2340 which you can buy for $300 at Bud's but in ARMSLIST sells for $600 !!!, or the P2022 that sells BNIB for $400 but sells for $500 or more in USED condition here. Nuts!!).

postcontent:
17 to 30 # range, shark release, just broken in, Mission Maniac Compound Bow

The Mission Maniac compound bow is a dual cam bow that is adjustable enough to ensure it suits a wide variety of people. The Maniac Dual Cam also combines nicely with parallel limbs, limb-based string suppressors and D-Amplifier string silencers to keep the noise and vibration to an absolute minimum.

It is all based around a fully machined aluminum reflex riser and this helps keep any jump down to a minimum.

The versatility of the bow and the great level of adjustment that is provided by the cam system ensures that the Maniac will be ideal for the young archer who will be looking for a formidable bow that will also grow with them. This doesn’t mean that the bow is only meant for the youngsters. In fact, it is a great hunting bow that will be appropriate for archers of all levels.

This rifle has two just perceptible pin prick defects on the stock... one on the toe of the butt stock, one on the bottom of the fore end.

I am the second owner, it's been in my safe undisturbed for about 7 or 8 years. I cleaned and lubed it, installed the sight and put it away. Shortly after I deployed to Iraq and forgot about it. It does not appear to have ever been fired.

Even though this is a replica of a firearm made before 1898 in a caliber not available through normal commercial trade, I will only transfer through an FFL.

Just how narrowly does the ATF define “normal commercial trade”? I don’t know… Even though 45-90 is not commonly available… it is nonetheless commercially available: http://ammoseek.com/ammo/45-90.

Further, even thought not an advisable thing to do and may prove destructive; commonly available 45-70 can be discharged by this firearm.

I hold my 2nd Amendment rights dear, and beyond that I have a security clearance I must protect…. So, I’d rather not run afoul of the ATF.
